  Directing Talent and Composition

In this video, I'll share tips and tricks for directing your characters and set design in Midjourney. We'll also get into composition and shot selection. Let's get started.

Ideal Prompt Style:

Cinematic Still of [Describe Characters, action, and setting], [Describe Shot Type and Composition], [Describe Style]

Example: A cinematic still of a woman drinking coffee in a New York Cafe at night, medium shot, in the style of David Fincher.

Note: Shorter Prompts Produce Better Results. If you aren't getting the results you are looking for, turn your style settings to Raw and weight your prompts to emphasize the parts of your prompt that are getting lost.

General Prompts for Instantly Improving Quality:

  • Cinematic Still
  • 8K
  • Ultra-Realistic

Shot Prompts:

  • Extreme Close-Up
  • Close-Up
  • Medium Close-Up
  • Medium Shot
  • Medium Long-Shot
  • Long-Shot (Reinforce Background Description to Pull Wide Shots)
  • Wide-Shot (Reinforce Background Description to Pull Wide Shots)
  • Ultra-Wide Shot (Reinforce Background Description to Pull Wide Shots)
  • Two Shot (Describe Action to See multiple characters.)
  • Over-the Shoulder Shot
  • Asymmetrical Shot
  • Symmetrical Shot

Style Ideas:

  • In the Style of [Director]
  • In the Style of [Cinematographer]
  • In the Style of [Era] [Genre] [Medium]
    • ex. In the style of a 1990s action movie
    • ex. In the style of a 2010s Drama TV Show
    • ex. In the style of a 1950s sci-fi movie

Note: If replicating a style pre-1980s, it can help to drop the 'cinematic still' tag at the beginning of your prompt.
